title: Start
---
$c1: You are awake. Stay still for one breath, then do exactly what I say.

$c1: Your head implant is live, your right arm is not fully calibrated, and the floor has entered evidence-burn lockdown. That means security will shoot first and let Compliance invent a reason later.

-> $c2: Who are you?
    <<jump Who>>
-> $c2: What did they do to me?
    <<jump Procedure>>
-> $c2: What do I need before I move on?
    <<jump Equipment>>
-> $c2: Tell me about the implant.
    <<jump NeuralPulse>>
-> $c2: How do I get out?
    <<jump Escape>>
===
title: ElianIntro
---
$c1: You are awake. Stay still for one breath, then do exactly what I say.

$c1: Your head implant is live, your right arm is not fully calibrated, and the floor has entered evidence-burn lockdown. That means security will shoot first and let Compliance invent a reason later.

-> $c2: Who are you?
    <<jump Who>>
-> $c2: What did they do to me?
    <<jump Procedure>>
-> $c2: What do I need before I move on?
    <<jump Equipment>>
-> $c2: Tell me about the implant.
    <<jump NeuralPulse>>
-> $c2: How do I get out?
    <<jump Escape>>
===
title: Who
---
$c1: Elian Voss. Assistant neurosystems lead, temporary traitor, and currently the only person on this floor who benefits from you leaving alive.

$c1: I signed off on monitoring, not the procedure. That distinction will matter to my conscience later. It will not matter to the guards now.

-> $c2: You helped make this happen.
    $c1: Yes. And I am helping you undo the part where they file you as broken equipment. Hate me while moving.
    <<jump Close>>
-> $c2: Why help me?
    $c1: Because the lockdown will purge patient records, staff witnesses, and failed subjects in that order. I am third on a very short list.
    <<jump Close>>
===
title: Procedure
---
$c1: They installed a cortical disruption mod and tied it into a prototype arm bus. You were supposed to wake slowly, under restraint, with a room full of handlers.

$c1: Instead, the calibration stack rejected the corporate leash. Good news: you can move. Bad news: every automated system on this floor now sees you as stolen property with a pulse.

-> $c2: Am I a full conversion?
    $c1: No. Mostly organic. Head implant, one arm, some ugly support leads. You are a test subject, not a tank. Do not let the panic make you stand in open lanes.
    <<jump Close>>
-> $c2: Can the implant kill me?
    $c1: If you overuse it, maybe. If you do not use it, the turret ahead definitely can. Choose the uncertainty that keeps you breathing.
    <<jump Close>>
===
title: Equipment
---
$c1: Storage is through the next door. Take the Level 1 card, the light pistol, the medgel, and the ammo cell. All of it.

$c1: The pistol is not a hero weapon. It is a way to create space. Medium range, clean line of sight, then move before someone smarter claims the angle.

-> $c2: I know how to shoot.
    $c1: Maybe. You do not know how this arm compensates recoil yet. Trust the sightline, not your memory.
    <<jump Close>>
-> $c2: What about the medgel?
    $c1: Use it when exposure costs more than pride. This floor was designed by people who think pain is a useful diagnostic.
    <<jump Close>>
===
title: NeuralPulse
---
$c1: Neural Pulse is the cyan module in your skull. It spikes control loops. Machines stall. Organic nervous systems lose the thread for a moment.

$c1: It is not magic. It needs range, line of sight, and a window. The calibration range has a turret because someone thought that was an acceptable teaching tool.

-> $c2: Use it on the turret?
    $c1: Yes. Find the safe angle first, pulse the turret, then cross while it is blind. If you stand in the lane and improvise, I will be very disappointed and you will be very perforated.
    <<jump Close>>
-> $c2: Use it on people?
    $c1: Briefly. A guard can recover. A scientist reaching an alarm panel can lose the one second that saves you ten minutes of gunfire.
    <<jump Close>>
===
title: Escape
---
$c1: South. Always south. Main lab, specimen ward, calibration range, containment corridor, checkpoint, elevator.

$c1: Do not clear rooms for pride. The exit is the objective. If a fight gives you a path, take the path.

-> $c2: What if the alarm goes off?
    $c1: Then the checkpoint gets meaner, not impossible. Stop the runner if you can. If you cannot, conserve ammunition and make the turret waste its advantage.
    <<jump Close>>
-> $c2: Are you coming with me?
    $c1: Glass says no. Survival says maybe later. Get to the elevator and I can try to meet you above the service stack.
    <<jump Close>>
===
title: Close
---
$c1: Move south. Use distance, use angles, and remember that escape counts even if the room behind you is still angry.
===
